;;; ============================================================
;;; 06-numerics
;;; numeric tower, arithmetic, number parsing/printing
;;; ============================================================
;;;
;;; Regression tripwires for numerics.  Each entry is pinned to a specific
;;; bug that was fixed -- this is NOT feature coverage.  Only Scheme-
;;; observable, non-spec regressions belong here; spec deviations go in
;;; R7RS-Compliance-Tests/, internal-only bugs in undercarriage gc_test.cpp.
;;; See 00-conventions.md for the full routing rule.
;;;
;;; HOW TO ADD A REGRESSION
;;;   - Append to the END of this file.  Tests run top-to-bottom; keep them
;;;     in chronological order (oldest bug first) so the file reads as a
;;;     timeline for this subsystem.
;;;   - Precede each case with a provenance comment so it stays meaningful:
;;;        ; REG <yyyy-mm-dd> -- <commit-or-issue> -- <one line: what broke>
;;;        ; Symptom: <what the user saw before the fix>
;;;   - Keep the reproducer MINIMAL, then give the expected result:
;;;        >>> (expression)
;;;        ==> expected             ; or:  %%% %any-error%
;;;
; REG 2026-06-20 -- known-open #3 -- cppScheme2 number reader used int64 for
;   rational literals and string->number, so any numerator/denominator past
;   int64 was mis-read.  The arithmetic tower + number->string were already
;   bignum-correct; only the READER lagged.  py was always correct.
; Symptom: (string->number "1/<bignum>") => #f; a bare bignum-integer string
;   => an inexact double; the bignum-rational literal => "malformed number".
>>> (string->number "1/170141183460469231731687303715884105728")
==> 1/170141183460469231731687303715884105728

>>> (string->number "170141183460469231731687303715884105728/3")
==> 170141183460469231731687303715884105728/3

>>> (string->number "170141183460469231731687303715884105728")
... ; a too-big integer must read as an EXACT bignum, not an inexact double
==> 170141183460469231731687303715884105728

>>> (exact? (string->number "170141183460469231731687303715884105728"))
==> #t

>>> (string->number "#x1/fffffffffffffffffffffffff")
... ; radix-prefixed bignum rationals must read too
==> 1/1267650600228229401496703205375

>>> 1/170141183460469231731687303715884105728
... ; the bignum-rational LITERAL reader (used to be "malformed number")
==> 1/170141183460469231731687303715884105728

>>> (= 1/170141183460469231731687303715884105728 (/ 1 (expt 2 127)))
... ; reader and arithmetic agree on the same exact value
==> #t
